Football is not only the worlds most dominant sport, but it has evolved financially as football clubs and players came to be seen as global commodities. In modern football, in order to be the best, you have to assemble the best team.  Powerhouse teams such as South Africa's Mamelodi Sundowns and Spanish giants Real Madrid can buy any player they like â€“â€“ sometimes not to strengthen the team, but to weaken their opponents. Read: Football's Best Moments In 2017 A recent example is the acquisition of New Zealand striker Jeremy Brockie by Mamelodi Sundowns, for a staggering reported fee of R14-million. The transfer certainly adds to the already powerful Sundowns arsenal, but it also weakens the team's direct opponents, which means they have a stranglehold on the league. Let's welcome Jeremy to the Sundowns Family Masandawana! #WelcomeJeremypic.twitter.com/e66XMnMFso  Take a look at five teams monopolising football with mega-purchases of star players from around the world. 1. Mamelodi Sundowns (South Africa)   In football, you're either a selling club or a buying club, and Sundowns is one of Africa's most powerful clubs when it comes to getting a player they want. Owned by South African billionaire Patrice Motsepe, the team can exercise their dominance in the transfer window and get the best players -- at the expense of their rivals. Read: From Soweto To Tshwane, Here Are 5 Reasons Why Teko Modise Is So Celebrated When you have such dominance, the chasing pack often fall short in competing, because they do not have the depth, firepower and money to compete with the mega-clubs. Sundowns have signed a lot of high-profile players from their direct rivals, including Teko Modise in 2011. Here are some of Sundowns' most high-profile signings, and the trophies they have won after the acquisitions: Jeremey Brockie - from SuperSport United - reported fee R14-Millionâš½ï¸ Rivaldo Coetzee - from Ajax Cape Town - reported fee R10-Millionâš½ï¸ Khama Billiat - from Ajax Cape Town -